<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870423-0141 </DOCNO><HL> Boesky Is SlatedTo Plead GuiltyTo Felony Today---By James B. StewartStaff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DD> 04/23/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS) </IN><DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ivan F. Boesky, the former arbitrager at the center of Wall Street's biggest insider-trading scandal, is scheduled to plead guilty today to one felony count in federal court, according to a court spokesman.    Mr. Boesky's scheduled appearance is part of his agreement with the government reached last November. Under that accord, the full terms of which haven't been disclosed, Mr. Boesky agreed to cooperate in the government's continuing investigation, waive indictment and plead guilty to a single, as-yet unidentified felony count. He faces a maximum five years in prison and $250,000 in fines.    Mr. Boesky is slated to plead before Judge Morris E. Lasker, who will thereby become the judge who determines Mr. Boesky's sentence. Judge Lasker is considered by lawyers as the most lenient of the federal judges in the Southern District of New York.    By permitting him to plead before Judge Lasker, government prosecutors are giving Mr. Boesky a rare prerogative. Ordinarily, a suspect who agrees to waive indictment and plead guilty is given six weeks from the date of the plea agreement to enter the plea. Since federal judges in Manhattan preside over pleas for two-week periods, the arrangement typically gives those who agree to plead guilty a choice of three sentencing judges.    Because it has been about five months since Mr. Boesky reached his plea agreement, lawyers have speculated that as part of that agreement, Mr. Boesky was given carte blanche to choose any sentencing judge.    Mr. Boesky's principal lawyer, Harvey Pitt of Fried, Frank, Harris, Shriver andamp; Jacobson, declined to comment on the terms of Mr. Boesky's agreement. A spokeswoman for Charles Carberry, the assistant U.S. attorney handling the Boesky case, declined comment.    Previously, government prosecutors and Securities and Exchange Commission officials have defended certain aspects of the agreement by emphasizing the value of Mr. Boesky's cooperation. So far, Mr. Boesky has implicated former investment banker Martin A. Siegel and Boyd L. Jefferies, former chairman of Jefferies Group Inc. -- each of whom pleaded guilty to two felonies -- and Michael Davidoff, Mr. Boesky's former head trader, who pleaded guilty to one felony.    The government's investigation continues, and Mr. Boesky is understood to have implicated others. Mr. Boesky was himself implicated by former investment banker Dennis B. Levine.    Last year Mr. Boesky settled related SEC charges by paying a record $100 million in fines and disgorged insider-trading profits. </TEXT></DOC>